<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="596" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1293]" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,907,932]" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">Discussion.</emphasis>
This species is closely related to 
<taxonomicName box="[729,898,908,932]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Melacoryphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="admirabilis">
<emphasis box="[729,898,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">M. admirabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it can be easily distinguished because 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Melacoryphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="admirabilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">M. admirabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the basal and external margin of the membrane very strongly surrounded by a white line, while in 
<taxonomicName box="[151,309,980,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Melacoryphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lagunensis">
<emphasis box="[151,309,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">M. lagunensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
this white line is not strongly marked. Also the apical third of the corium in 
<taxonomicName box="[1190,1358,980,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Melacoryphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="admirabilis">
<emphasis box="[1190,1358,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">M. admirabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is red, while in 
<taxonomicName box="[247,404,1016,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Melacoryphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lagunensis">
<emphasis box="[247,404,1016,1040]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">M. lagunensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is usually dark brown with just the margin with some red coloration. The front margin of the pronotum is red in 
<taxonomicName box="[371,532,1052,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Melacoryphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="admirabilis">
<emphasis box="[371,532,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">M admirabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and brownish red in 
<taxonomicName box="[777,936,1052,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Melacoryphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lagunensis">
<emphasis box="[777,936,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">M. lagunensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The pygophore has ventral margin slightly sinuated in 
<taxonomicName box="[280,437,1088,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Melacoryphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lagunensis">
<emphasis box="[280,437,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">M. lagunensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[452,519,1087,1112]" captionStart="FIGURES 3" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1189,1212]" captionTargetBox="[262,1321,198,1161]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[256,1330,193,1168]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 3 – - 6. 3 – 4. Melacoryphus lagunensis new species. 3, Pygophore. 4, Paramere. 5 – 6. Melacoryphus admirabilis (Uhler). 5, Pygophore. 6, Paramere." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227206/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">
Fig. 
<number box="[505,519,1088,1112]" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
), while in 
<taxonomicName box="[640,806,1088,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Melacoryphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="admirabilis">
<emphasis box="[640,806,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">M. admirabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is rounded (
<figureCitation box="[945,1007,1087,1112]" captionStart="FIGURES 3" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1189,1212]" captionTargetBox="[262,1321,198,1161]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[256,1330,193,1168]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 3 – - 6. 3 – 4. Melacoryphus lagunensis new species. 3, Pygophore. 4, Paramere. 5 – 6. Melacoryphus admirabilis (Uhler). 5, Pygophore. 6, Paramere." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227206/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">
Fig 
<number box="[991,1007,1087,1112]" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
). The paramere with blade almost at a right angle to shank, and just slightly curved in 
<taxonomicName box="[681,837,1124,1148]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Melacoryphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lagunensis">
<emphasis box="[681,837,1124,1148]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">M. lagunensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[852,920,1124,1149]" captionStart="FIGURES 3" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1189,1212]" captionTargetBox="[262,1321,198,1161]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[256,1330,193,1168]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 3 – - 6. 3 – 4. Melacoryphus lagunensis new species. 3, Pygophore. 4, Paramere. 5 – 6. Melacoryphus admirabilis (Uhler). 5, Pygophore. 6, Paramere." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227206/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">
Fig. 
<number box="[904,920,1124,1148]" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
), while in 
<taxonomicName box="[1038,1204,1124,1148]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Melacoryphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="admirabilis">
<emphasis box="[1038,1204,1124,1148]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">M. admirabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the blade is strongly curved (
<figureCitation box="[242,311,1159,1184]" captionStart="FIGURES 3" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1189,1212]" captionTargetBox="[262,1321,198,1161]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[256,1330,193,1168]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 3 – - 6. 3 – 4. Melacoryphus lagunensis new species. 3, Pygophore. 4, Paramere. 5 – 6. Melacoryphus admirabilis (Uhler). 5, Pygophore. 6, Paramere." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227206/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">
Fig. 
<number box="[295,311,1159,1184]" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1293]" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">
In the key to species of 
<bibRefCitation author="Slater" box="[461,643,1196,1221]" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" refString="Slater, A. (1992) A Genus Level Revision of Western Hemisphere Lygaeinae (Heteroptera: Lygaeidae) with Keys to Species. The University of Kansas Science Bulletin, 55 (1), 1 - 56." type="journal article" year="1992">
A. Slater (
<number box="[575,635,1196,1220]" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" value="1992.0">1992</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[654,811,1196,1220]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Melacoryphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lagunensis">
<emphasis box="[654,811,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">M. lagunensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
runs to couplet 
<number box="[989,1005,1196,1220]" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" value="4.0">4</number>
, as 
<taxonomicName box="[1046,1212,1196,1220]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Melacoryphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="admirabilis">
<emphasis box="[1046,1212,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="596">M. admirabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and although it has the basal margin of the membrane white, and the membrane brown to black with white margins, most of the corium and clavus are brown to black, having only less than a quarter of the apical part of the corium reddish.
</paragraph>
